00:01:19.965 --> 00:01:23.020
in education as we see it.

00:01:23.020 --> 00:01:24.630
So let's start with the why.

00:01:24.630 --> 00:01:27.290
Like, why did we originally
create Google Expeditions?

00:01:27.290 --> 00:01:30.190
And why do we think VR
platforms like Daydream

00:01:30.190 --> 00:01:33.489
will offer so much potential
for educators and learners?

00:01:33.489 --> 00:01:35.030
Why should developers
like yourselves

00:01:35.030 --> 00:01:38.046
be interested in developing
educational apps for VR?

00:01:38.046 --> 00:01:41.090
So let's start with a
quick show of hands.

00:01:41.090 --> 00:01:43.750
How many of you remember
studying really, really hard

00:01:43.750 --> 00:01:45.610
for a test in school?

00:01:45.610 --> 00:01:47.390
How many?

00:01:47.390 --> 00:01:48.950
Most of you.

00:01:48.950 --> 00:01:50.860
How many of you
forgot everything

00:01:50.860 --> 00:01:54.010
that you studied the
second after the test?

00:01:54.010 --> 00:01:55.934
Exactly the same number, right?

00:01:55.934 --> 00:01:58.100
How many of you think you
could do well in that test

00:01:58.100 --> 00:01:59.460
again right now?

00:01:59.460 --> 00:02:00.045
Not a lot.

00:02:00.045 --> 00:02:01.580
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:01.580 --> 00:02:03.400
So how many of you
remember a trip

00:02:03.400 --> 00:02:05.860
that you've taken to an
interesting place, a country,

00:02:05.860 --> 00:02:07.670
a museum, something like that?

00:02:07.670 --> 00:02:09.539
About the same number.

00:02:09.539 --> 00:02:14.170
How many of you can recall
details about that trip?

00:02:14.170 --> 00:02:15.790
A lot of you, right?

00:02:15.790 --> 00:02:17.320
So therein lies
one of the reasons

00:02:17.320 --> 00:02:21.550
why we find the emergence of
widely accessible VR technology

00:02:21.550 --> 00:02:24.340
so exciting for education.

00:02:24.340 --> 00:02:26.700
Google I/O is no place to
temper one's enthusiasm.

00:02:26.700 --> 00:02:28.730
So I'll make a bold
claim that many of us who

00:02:28.730 --> 00:02:30.770
think about educational
technology, VR

00:02:30.770 --> 00:02:33.290
is the thing we've
been waiting for,

00:02:33.290 --> 00:02:36.290
because it allows us to address
one of the most important,

00:02:36.290 --> 00:02:38.650
but neglected areas of learning.

00:02:38.650 --> 00:02:42.640
And I want to spend a few
minutes digging into why.

00:02:42.640 --> 00:02:45.631
So to start with, let's take a
really, really big step back.

00:02:45.631 --> 00:02:47.130
Historically, most
of the technology

00:02:47.130 --> 00:02:49.760
that we've developed
to aid learning

00:02:49.760 --> 00:02:52.370
has been aimed to enable
access to information--

00:02:52.370 --> 00:02:56.280
facts, details, other
observations about the world.

00:02:56.280 --> 00:02:59.960
And for most of human
history, a smart person

00:02:59.960 --> 00:03:02.950
has basically been someone
who knew a lot of facts.

00:03:02.950 --> 00:03:05.840
And fact retention is what a
lot of the technology that we've

00:03:05.840 --> 00:03:07.930
built directly supports.

00:03:07.930 --> 00:03:11.370
I'm talking about things
like the book, right?

00:03:11.370 --> 00:03:14.630
Or libraries of books, a
catalog that lets you easily

00:03:14.630 --> 00:03:18.960
access tons and tons
of information quickly.

00:03:18.960 --> 00:03:21.690
Search engines, like one
you might recognize here,

00:03:21.690 --> 00:03:24.730
have only served to make
this kind of fact retrieval

00:03:24.730 --> 00:03:29.880
breathtakingly fast,
comprehensive, and easy.

00:03:29.880 --> 00:03:33.680
Even the rapid growth of
technology like laptops,

00:03:33.680 --> 00:03:36.640
and tablets, and
smartphones in schools

00:03:36.640 --> 00:03:41.690
has only really served to help
you assimilate information

00:03:41.690 --> 00:03:43.477
and then turn
around and evaluate

00:03:43.477 --> 00:03:45.560
how well you did in absorbing
it and recalling it.

00:03:48.460 --> 00:03:50.919
But while information is
super, super important,

00:03:50.919 --> 00:03:52.460
it's not even close
to the full story

00:03:52.460 --> 00:03:53.770
when it comes to learning.

00:03:53.770 --> 00:03:56.650
Let me give you one
example of this.

00:03:56.650 --> 00:03:58.770
Here is a math problem.

00:03:58.770 --> 00:04:01.370
"There are 26 goats
and 10 sheep on a boat.

00:04:01.370 --> 00:04:04.260
How old is the
captain of the boat?"

00:04:04.260 --> 00:04:05.970
So a study done in
the US to a bunch

00:04:05.970 --> 00:04:09.570
of fifth graders in the
'90s asked this question.

00:04:09.570 --> 00:04:12.040
And three-fourths
of those students

00:04:12.040 --> 00:04:14.860
produced a numerical
answer to this question.

00:04:14.860 --> 00:04:17.459
The most common answer was 36.

00:04:17.459 --> 00:04:18.779
There were some 16s.

00:04:18.779 --> 00:04:20.822
And amazingly,
there was one 260.

00:04:20.822 --> 00:04:23.980
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:23.980 --> 00:04:26.729
A quote from one of the students
who answered 36 said, "Well,

00:04:26.729 --> 00:04:29.020
for this type of problem,
you need to add, or subtract,

00:04:29.020 --> 00:04:30.080
or multiply.

00:04:30.080 --> 00:04:32.245
And for this one, it
seemed it was best to add."

00:04:32.245 --> 00:04:33.520
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:33.520 --> 00:04:34.780
Right?

00:04:34.780 --> 00:04:37.340
And the important point, these
kids are not stupid at all.

00:04:37.340 --> 00:04:39.324
These are smart kids.

00:04:39.324 --> 00:04:41.490
But they're kids for whom
the traditional approaches

00:04:41.490 --> 00:04:43.880
to teaching mathematics
are failing.

00:04:43.880 --> 00:04:48.100
Let me give you one little
bit more complicated example.

00:04:48.100 --> 00:04:50.710
A study done in the '90s found
that when students were taught

00:04:50.710 --> 00:04:54.230
geography in a traditional way
by memorizing all the states

00:04:54.230 --> 00:04:56.760
and where they go and the
state capitals with a worksheet

00:04:56.760 --> 00:05:00.950
like this, they were largely
incapable of naming or placing

00:05:00.950 --> 00:05:03.070
those same states in
the correct places

00:05:03.070 --> 00:05:05.480
when the borders were
removed like that.

00:05:05.480 --> 00:05:09.420
They were basically clueless
the second the map changed.

00:05:09.420 --> 00:05:11.619
But the study found that
another group of students

00:05:11.619 --> 00:05:13.410
who had spent some time
discussing concepts

00:05:13.410 --> 00:05:16.400
like why rivers and
mountain ranges are natural

00:05:16.400 --> 00:05:19.160
borders-- they were much more
capable of placing states

00:05:19.160 --> 00:05:21.210
in the right spots.

00:05:21.210 --> 00:05:24.060
And the reason that's important
is that simple techniques

00:05:24.060 --> 00:05:27.520
that literally, in this case,
ground information about which

00:05:27.520 --> 00:05:31.769
states are where serve
students to understand

00:05:31.769 --> 00:05:33.310
the important concepts
of why-- like,

00:05:33.310 --> 00:05:35.590
why are the borders
where they are.

00:05:35.590 --> 00:05:37.200
And learning this
way is powerful,

00:05:37.200 --> 00:05:40.230
because it allows for much more
improved knowledge transfer.

00:05:40.230 --> 00:05:42.590
It allows you to apply the
same thing you learned there

00:05:42.590 --> 00:05:43.302
somewhere else.

00:05:43.302 --> 00:05:45.260
So you could logically
apply these same lessons

00:05:45.260 --> 00:05:47.120
to a map of Europe or whatever.

00:05:47.120 --> 00:05:50.530
Let me give you another
very different example.

00:05:50.530 --> 00:05:52.720
We've long known that
we have really, really

00:05:52.720 --> 00:05:55.350
powerful and innate
spatial memories,

00:05:55.350 --> 00:05:57.780
even if we didn't
understand the mechanisms.

00:05:57.780 --> 00:06:00.490
This is the reason why most of
you guys can remember the trips

00:06:00.490 --> 00:06:03.930
and none of us can
remember the test.

00:06:03.930 --> 00:06:06.064
And here's actually a
medieval representation

00:06:06.064 --> 00:06:07.730
of the brain that
tried to understand it

00:06:07.730 --> 00:06:09.920
as actually a series
of spaces where

00:06:09.920 --> 00:06:13.670
you crammed memories and facts,
like an attic or something.

00:06:13.670 --> 00:06:16.020
They actually
weren't that far off.

00:06:16.020 --> 00:06:18.420
It's the same insight
that has given rise

00:06:18.420 --> 00:06:21.150
to that mnemonic device
called a memory palace,

00:06:21.150 --> 00:06:22.420
or a mind palace.

00:06:22.420 --> 00:06:24.420
For those of you who
don't know what that is,

00:06:24.420 --> 00:06:26.450
it basically involves
using our memory

00:06:26.450 --> 00:06:28.880
of a place, or better
spatial memory, the rooms

00:06:28.880 --> 00:06:32.110
in a familiar building like
your house or your street,

00:06:32.110 --> 00:06:35.180
as a structure in which to place
the arbitrary facts that you

00:06:35.180 --> 00:06:37.880
remember, say, in this
picture, like a large number

00:06:37.880 --> 00:06:39.896
of amphibious species.

00:06:39.896 --> 00:06:41.520
So each thing that
you want to remember

00:06:41.520 --> 00:06:43.144
gets associated with
the physical space

00:06:43.144 --> 00:06:44.427
that you already know.

00:06:44.427 --> 00:06:46.010
And then when you
want to recall them,

00:06:46.010 --> 00:06:47.889
you visualize that
space you know.

00:06:47.889 --> 00:06:50.180
And you use them as a trigger
for that set of arbitrary

00:06:50.180 --> 00:06:51.030
facts.

00:06:51.030 --> 00:06:53.930
And we've known that this
works for a long time.

00:06:53.930 --> 00:06:57.670
Cicero used it to remember
long, long speeches.

00:06:57.670 --> 00:07:00.570
But it's a capability
that traditional academics

00:07:00.570 --> 00:07:02.510
rarely, rarely tap.

00:07:02.510 --> 00:07:05.490
It's one that's easy to
see VR making use of them.

00:07:09.810 --> 00:07:11.360
It's only recently
that we've really

00:07:11.360 --> 00:07:13.250
begun to understand why
this works that way,

00:07:13.250 --> 00:07:14.930
at least scientifically.

00:07:14.930 --> 00:07:17.960
The last 30 or so years
have seen a revolution

00:07:17.960 --> 00:07:19.870
in the study of
cognition, and especially

00:07:19.870 --> 00:07:22.620
in the study of the
science of learning.

00:07:22.620 --> 00:07:24.760
For one, we understand
that learning actually

00:07:24.760 --> 00:07:26.930
changes the physiology
of the brain.

00:07:26.930 --> 00:07:28.305
And we can actually
look for that

00:07:28.305 --> 00:07:31.140
when we're studying learning.

00:07:31.140 --> 00:07:34.910
We also know-- we have
scientific evidence

00:07:34.910 --> 00:07:37.490
that being smart is not
about being informed.

00:07:37.490 --> 00:07:40.400
For instance, studies have
shown that very young children

00:07:40.400 --> 00:07:42.430
with very little
information quickly

00:07:42.430 --> 00:07:45.944
understand fundamental concepts
of numbers, physics, and logic.

00:07:45.944 --> 00:07:47.610
And they can learn
these really quickly.

00:07:47.610 --> 00:07:50.170
So it turns out that
kids like my 8-month-old

00:07:50.170 --> 00:07:53.440
are in fact very smart,
very ignorant little experts

00:07:53.440 --> 00:07:54.840
in learning.

00:07:54.840 --> 00:07:56.590
And this one remains
a novice in sleeping.

00:07:59.430 --> 00:08:01.730
And now that we have all
supercomputers in our pockets,

00:08:01.730 --> 00:08:04.709
the notion of smartness
really needs to change, right?

00:08:04.709 --> 00:08:06.250
Because being smart
isn't about being

00:08:06.250 --> 00:08:08.780
able to repeat and
remember information.

00:08:08.780 --> 00:08:12.170
Technology does an amazing
job of doing that for us.

00:08:12.170 --> 00:08:14.860
Being smart is being able to
effectively use information

00:08:14.860 --> 00:08:17.190
and locate it within concepts.

00:08:17.190 --> 00:08:19.510
So as Herbert Simon
says here, the new smart

00:08:19.510 --> 00:08:22.730
is being able to sort out what's
deserving of our attention.

00:08:22.730 --> 00:08:25.850
And given that most of us have
jobs today that didn't even

00:08:25.850 --> 00:08:28.444
exist when we were born,
the ability to learn

00:08:28.444 --> 00:08:29.610
is more important than ever.

00:08:32.150 --> 00:08:35.380
OK, I'm sure you're all
surprised that I'm not

00:08:35.380 --> 00:08:38.440
a cognitive scientist given
my 30 second recap of 30

00:08:38.440 --> 00:08:40.190
years of nuanced study.

00:08:40.190 --> 00:08:42.860
But the thing that I'm
excited to take away from this

00:08:42.860 --> 00:08:45.730
is that it confirms what
great educators have long

00:08:45.730 --> 00:08:50.080
known-- that the days
that people learn best,

00:08:50.080 --> 00:08:52.700
that the teachers who inspire
their students the best,

00:08:52.700 --> 00:08:55.120
that the days when school
is the most effective

00:08:55.120 --> 00:08:57.050
are the ones that put
learners in the position

00:08:57.050 --> 00:08:59.120
to discover for
themselves, to organize

00:08:59.120 --> 00:09:02.200
those facts into concepts,
to turn misconceptions

00:09:02.200 --> 00:09:04.330
into metacognition, or
these moments where you're

00:09:04.330 --> 00:09:06.340
aware of your own learning
and you can actually

00:09:06.340 --> 00:09:07.867
think and reflect on it.

00:09:07.867 --> 00:09:09.450
And even if we haven't
had the science

00:09:09.450 --> 00:09:11.230
to prove it until
recently, we've

00:09:11.230 --> 00:09:13.230
known about this for a
really, really long time.

00:09:16.080 --> 00:09:18.310
It almost seems trite
when you read it,

00:09:18.310 --> 00:09:21.260
but Aristotle is actually being
sort of profoundly insightful

00:09:21.260 --> 00:09:23.690
when he claims that we
learn by doing things.

00:09:23.690 --> 00:09:25.890
It's all the more profound
when you go into schools,

00:09:25.890 --> 00:09:30.177
and you see how little learning
actually happens by doing.

00:09:30.177 --> 00:09:31.760
Even more contemporary
people like one

00:09:31.760 --> 00:09:33.996
of the great thinkers
of pedagogy, John Dewey,

00:09:33.996 --> 00:09:35.620
was telling us 100
years ago that if we

00:09:35.620 --> 00:09:38.078
want to foster learning, we
have to give students something

00:09:38.078 --> 00:09:40.760
to do, not something to learn.

00:09:40.760 --> 00:09:43.710
And this is when ed tech was
like books on a chalkboard,

00:09:43.710 --> 00:09:46.090
right?

00:09:46.090 --> 00:09:48.260
One of our most influential
current thinkers

00:09:48.260 --> 00:09:50.474
about educational technology,
Seymour Papert-- he

00:09:50.474 --> 00:09:52.390
was the guy that created
the first programming

00:09:52.390 --> 00:09:54.325
language for kids--
noted that teachers

00:09:54.325 --> 00:09:55.950
should concern
themselves with creating

00:09:55.950 --> 00:09:59.420
the conditions for learning
rather than providing

00:09:59.420 --> 00:10:00.335
information.

00:10:00.335 --> 00:10:01.710
And that's one of
the reasons why

00:10:01.710 --> 00:10:04.310
he was so passionate about
the freedom of expression kids

00:10:04.310 --> 00:10:07.690
get by learning how
to write software.

00:10:07.690 --> 00:10:09.880
But even though we've
long had these intuitions,

00:10:09.880 --> 00:10:11.440
we've had experts
telling us this,

00:10:11.440 --> 00:10:13.410
and now we have science
confirming this,

00:10:13.410 --> 00:10:17.766
we don't really have the
technology to scale this stuff.

00:10:17.766 --> 00:10:18.390
Think about it.

00:10:18.390 --> 00:10:22.190
The technology that
we use is amazing.

00:10:22.190 --> 00:10:24.340
My favorite days that
I remember as a student

00:10:24.340 --> 00:10:27.757
were in science labs, being
able to look at things up close,

00:10:27.757 --> 00:10:29.340
not being able to
predict the outcome.

00:10:29.340 --> 00:10:30.810
These are amazing moments.

00:10:30.810 --> 00:10:32.780
But this technology is
really hard to scale.

00:10:32.780 --> 00:10:33.520
It's expensive.

00:10:33.520 --> 00:10:34.500
It breaks.

00:10:34.500 --> 00:10:37.400
And it's constrained by time
and safety considerations.

00:10:37.400 --> 00:10:39.470
In many, many
countries and places,

00:10:39.470 --> 00:10:42.240
these moments just don't happen.

00:10:42.240 --> 00:10:44.810
And even more recently,
we've seen this explosion

00:10:44.810 --> 00:10:47.010
of really, really
cool robots and stuff

00:10:47.010 --> 00:10:49.480
in schools that help you
learn how to code and help you

00:10:49.480 --> 00:10:50.300
do logic.

00:10:50.300 --> 00:10:52.050
Again, though, these
things are expensive.

00:10:52.050 --> 00:10:53.290
They're hard to scale.

00:10:53.290 --> 00:10:55.540
And they're relatively limited
in the number of things

00:10:55.540 --> 00:10:56.700
that they can do.

00:10:56.700 --> 00:11:00.200
Even the classic technology
of this big yellow bus

00:11:00.200 --> 00:11:03.270
that takes us on field trips,
again, amazing moments.

00:11:03.270 --> 00:11:05.280
It's really expensive.

00:11:05.280 --> 00:11:09.330
And it's super-limited
by time and space.

00:11:09.330 --> 00:11:13.040
VR gives us new-found
powers to scale and make

00:11:13.040 --> 00:11:16.500
experiential, dynamic,
engaging learning a much, much

00:11:16.500 --> 00:11:18.250
more regular occurrence.

00:11:18.250 --> 00:11:20.070
And the economics
of VR for schools

00:11:20.070 --> 00:11:22.290
looks really different
when a single device

00:11:22.290 --> 00:11:26.300
can be your science lab-- can
be your programmable robot-- can

00:11:26.300 --> 00:11:29.850
give you access to museums,
and can be your school bus.

00:11:29.850 --> 00:11:31.480
The very cool thing
that is happening

00:11:31.480 --> 00:11:35.520
is that the same technological
revolution that demands we all

00:11:35.520 --> 00:11:39.060
get to be better learners is
the same technology that's

00:11:39.060 --> 00:11:41.220
going to help us scale
that type of learning.

00:11:41.220 --> 00:11:44.010
And to talk about our first
project towards that goal,

00:11:44.010 --> 00:11:46.090
I'd like to invite Jen.

00:11:46.090 --> 00:11:47.590
[APPLAUSE]

00:11:51.710 --> 00:11:54.380
JENNIFER HOLLAND: Thanks,
Ben, for the history lesson.

00:11:54.380 --> 00:11:58.295
So I'm program manager
on Google Expeditions.

00:11:58.295 --> 00:12:01.110
And at Google I/O last
year, we announced

00:12:01.110 --> 00:12:05.390
Expeditions, a new virtual
reality app for schools.

00:12:05.390 --> 00:12:08.220
And instead of just
releasing that app,

00:12:08.220 --> 00:12:11.310
we actually piloted
with hundreds of schools

00:12:11.310 --> 00:12:14.500
all over the world to better
understand how this could

00:12:14.500 --> 00:12:16.800
be a powerful learning tool.

00:12:16.800 --> 00:12:21.000
And it represents the first
deployment of VR technology

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:25.010
in schools at scale.

00:12:25.010 --> 00:12:28.090
And so for those of you that
might not know what Expeditions

00:12:28.090 --> 00:12:30.680
is, it combines three things.

00:12:30.680 --> 00:12:33.850
One, it's software
built alongside teachers

00:12:33.850 --> 00:12:39.430
and students-- two, immersive
virtual reality content--

00:12:39.430 --> 00:12:43.790
and three, devices that are
available to any school.

00:12:43.790 --> 00:12:48.350
All you need is a smartphone,
a VR viewer, and a tablet.

00:12:48.350 --> 00:12:51.940
And you're able to teleport
all over the world.

00:12:51.940 --> 00:12:54.290
Actually, you can teleport
all over the Universe

00:12:54.290 --> 00:12:55.670
with Expeditions.

00:12:55.670 --> 00:13:00.280
And you can laugh and learn
like you're actually there.

00:13:00.280 --> 00:13:02.870
And so the
expeditions themselves

00:13:02.870 --> 00:13:06.360
are comprised of virtual
reality panoramas.

00:13:06.360 --> 00:13:08.950
There are 360-degree
photo spheres

00:13:08.950 --> 00:13:11.780
that are annotated with
descriptions and points

00:13:11.780 --> 00:13:14.560
of interests, which make it
really easy for the teacher

00:13:14.560 --> 00:13:17.980
to actually incorporate
it into their lesson.

00:13:17.980 --> 00:13:21.410
And when a teacher points
something out on their tablet,

00:13:21.410 --> 00:13:25.120
an arrow pops up on the student
device directing the students

00:13:25.120 --> 00:13:29.260
to look in that
particular direction.

00:13:29.260 --> 00:13:32.370
And as Ben mentioned, we
were able to bring over

00:13:32.370 --> 00:13:37.020
1 million students on an
expedition in 11 countries.

00:13:37.020 --> 00:13:40.390
And I want you to think about
that number for a second.

00:13:40.390 --> 00:13:42.450
Imagine Shoreline
Amphitheater here

00:13:42.450 --> 00:13:45.880
at Google I/O filled
with students.

00:13:45.880 --> 00:13:48.850
Every single seat is a student.

00:13:48.850 --> 00:13:51.810
Now, multiply that by 150.

00:13:51.810 --> 00:13:53.860
And that's how many
students have actually

00:13:53.860 --> 00:13:56.720
gone on an expedition
this school year.

00:13:56.720 --> 00:13:58.420
And it's still happening today.

00:13:58.420 --> 00:14:01.200
If you were to pull out your
phone and look on Twitter

00:14:01.200 --> 00:14:03.450
and look at the hashtag
#GoogleExpeditions,

00:14:03.450 --> 00:14:07.320
you are going to see so many
kids smiling and excited

00:14:07.320 --> 00:14:08.120
about learning.

00:14:08.120 --> 00:14:09.786
And I definitely
encourage you to do it.

00:14:09.786 --> 00:14:12.760
Just do it after our session.

00:14:12.760 --> 00:14:15.760
And we're able to reach that
many students because of how

00:14:15.760 --> 00:14:18.370
accessible the hardware is.

00:14:18.370 --> 00:14:21.520
You don't need all these
cords and fancy headsets.

00:14:21.520 --> 00:14:26.100
You just need devices that
you can pull off the shelf.

00:14:26.100 --> 00:14:28.660
So let's take a look at
what one of those classrooms

00:14:28.660 --> 00:14:29.810
is experiencing.

