00:16:24.220 --> 00:16:25.975
JENNIFER HOLLAND: The
best part of my job

00:16:25.975 --> 00:16:27.600
throughout this whole
year has actually

00:16:27.600 --> 00:16:31.670
been able to go and visit
these schools-- visit

00:16:31.670 --> 00:16:33.980
students like Lance.

00:16:33.980 --> 00:16:36.544
So initially, when we
thought about Expeditions,

00:16:36.544 --> 00:16:38.210
we thought it would
be about taking kids

00:16:38.210 --> 00:16:41.210
to the most majestic
places all over the world.

00:16:41.210 --> 00:16:44.450
We thought it was like taking
students to the Taj Mahal.

00:16:44.450 --> 00:16:47.490
We thought it might be about
exploring the Great Barrier

00:16:47.490 --> 00:16:48.690
Reef or Mt.

00:16:48.690 --> 00:16:50.890
Everest, or even Mars.

00:16:50.890 --> 00:16:53.440
But what we quickly found
out was that Expeditions

00:16:53.440 --> 00:16:56.100
is so much more than that.

00:16:56.100 --> 00:16:57.610
It's actually
about enabling kids

00:16:57.610 --> 00:16:59.800
to visit places that
might be nearby,

00:16:59.800 --> 00:17:02.199
but they might not
be able to get to.

00:17:02.199 --> 00:17:03.740
So this picture is
actually a picture

00:17:03.740 --> 00:17:07.430
from a middle school, Pryor
Middle School, in Montana.

00:17:07.430 --> 00:17:10.980
And many of the students
are of Crow descent.

00:17:10.980 --> 00:17:14.589
And every August, there's this
huge powwow and celebration

00:17:14.589 --> 00:17:17.589
of the Crow tribe that
happens in Montana.

00:17:17.589 --> 00:17:20.319
And many of these students
who live three hours away

00:17:20.319 --> 00:17:23.750
from where the celebration is
weren't actually able to go.

00:17:23.750 --> 00:17:27.030
So we took our Odyssey
rig-- Google's Jump camera

00:17:27.030 --> 00:17:28.850
with GoPro, and we brought it.

00:17:28.850 --> 00:17:31.790
And we placed it right in
the middle of that powwow

00:17:31.790 --> 00:17:35.250
and right next to the horses
so that all the students

00:17:35.250 --> 00:17:36.650
could see the horse parade.

00:17:36.650 --> 00:17:39.080
And we took it inside
tepees so that students

00:17:39.080 --> 00:17:42.250
could see how a tepee is made.

00:17:42.250 --> 00:17:44.610
And we built those expeditions.

00:17:44.610 --> 00:17:46.440
And then we took it
to the middle school

00:17:46.440 --> 00:17:50.280
so that those students could all
participate in the celebration.

00:17:50.280 --> 00:17:53.190
But what was amazing was
that those expeditions

00:17:53.190 --> 00:17:59.180
were used around the world
to celebrate that weekend.

00:17:59.180 --> 00:18:02.970
And we also know that historical
moments are also really

00:18:02.970 --> 00:18:04.770
important teaching moments.

00:18:04.770 --> 00:18:08.210
But they sometimes are
difficult to facilitate.

00:18:08.210 --> 00:18:11.770
So we've actually found a
way to include rich overlays

00:18:11.770 --> 00:18:14.240
and use historical
sound recordings

00:18:14.240 --> 00:18:17.080
to evoke a historical setting.

00:18:17.080 --> 00:18:19.940
And one of the other
cool things about this

00:18:19.940 --> 00:18:23.400
is that we were able to use
some of the same computer vision

00:18:23.400 --> 00:18:26.230
techniques that the
Street View team uses

00:18:26.230 --> 00:18:29.390
to align this automatically.

00:18:29.390 --> 00:18:32.030
And so let's take, for
example, this recent expedition

00:18:32.030 --> 00:18:35.470
we created in partnership with
Ken Burns, and Major League

00:18:35.470 --> 00:18:39.090
Baseball, and PBS to celebrate
Jackie Robinson's life

00:18:39.090 --> 00:18:41.010
and legacy.

00:18:41.010 --> 00:18:44.130
This panorama is one
scene from that tour.

00:18:44.130 --> 00:18:46.450
And it's of the
March on Washington

00:18:46.450 --> 00:18:50.050
and how Jackie Robinson
played a really critical role

00:18:50.050 --> 00:18:54.050
in the Civil Rights fight
for African-Americans.

00:18:54.050 --> 00:18:59.160
And this 360-degree
panorama was taken recently.

00:18:59.160 --> 00:19:02.800
And we found a historical photo
from the March on Washington

00:19:02.800 --> 00:19:05.240
and overlaid it
in the exact spot

00:19:05.240 --> 00:19:08.410
of where it was taken so that
students could get a better

00:19:08.410 --> 00:19:11.890
understanding of that
significance of what took place

00:19:11.890 --> 00:19:13.480
over 53 years ago.

00:19:16.150 --> 00:19:20.180
And current events are just
as equally important teaching

00:19:20.180 --> 00:19:21.110
moments.

00:19:21.110 --> 00:19:24.280
But they too are often
difficult to facilitate.

00:19:24.280 --> 00:19:27.820
Take two of the most
catastrophic nuclear events

00:19:27.820 --> 00:19:31.280
that took place--
Chernobyl and Fukushima.

00:19:31.280 --> 00:19:35.970
These are places that you would
never, ever take students to.

00:19:35.970 --> 00:19:38.660
But it's actually a really
important teaching moment.

00:19:38.660 --> 00:19:42.190
And teachers have had to rely
on videos and news articles

00:19:42.190 --> 00:19:44.190
to explain what happened.

00:19:44.190 --> 00:19:46.820
But starting today,
schools participating

00:19:46.820 --> 00:19:49.630
in the Expeditions Pioneer
Program in our beta

00:19:49.630 --> 00:19:53.470
are actually able to go and
visit Chernobyl and Fukushima

00:19:53.470 --> 00:19:57.210
and see for themselves
what happened.

00:19:57.210 --> 00:19:59.520
And this expedition we
have been creating-- this

00:19:59.520 --> 00:20:01.110
is the first current
event expedition

00:20:01.110 --> 00:20:06.010
that we've created in
partnership with Getty Images.

00:20:06.010 --> 00:20:08.400
And we're also going to be
working with Associated Press

00:20:08.400 --> 00:20:12.690
to create more current event
expeditions so that students

00:20:12.690 --> 00:20:15.510
all over the world will
be able to visit places

00:20:15.510 --> 00:20:19.630
that time, and safety,
and geographic distance

00:20:19.630 --> 00:20:21.200
make virtually impossible.

00:20:24.870 --> 00:20:27.670
And beyond the
curriculum, we quickly

00:20:27.670 --> 00:20:30.850
learn that there's even
broader learning opportunities

00:20:30.850 --> 00:20:32.460
with Expeditions.

00:20:32.460 --> 00:20:34.970
And it was the vision of
others that helped encourage

00:20:34.970 --> 00:20:38.190
us to expand beyond that.

00:20:38.190 --> 00:20:40.410
And so the First
Lady saw Expeditions.

00:20:40.410 --> 00:20:43.360
And she had a vision for
how she could use it as part

00:20:43.360 --> 00:20:45.320
of her Reach Higher Initiative.

00:20:45.320 --> 00:20:47.960
For those of you who might not
be familiar about the Reach

00:20:47.960 --> 00:20:49.550
Higher Initiative,
the First Lady

00:20:49.550 --> 00:20:52.940
has been encouraging
students all over the US

00:20:52.940 --> 00:20:54.910
to apply and go to college.

00:20:54.910 --> 00:20:57.800
And she saw Expeditions
as a great tool

00:20:57.800 --> 00:21:01.040
to use in order to be
able to enable students

00:21:01.040 --> 00:21:03.230
to actually visit colleges.

00:21:03.230 --> 00:21:05.150
There are a lot of
students out there

00:21:05.150 --> 00:21:08.660
who lack the role models who
might have gone to college.

00:21:08.660 --> 00:21:11.170
And they themselves might
not be able to imagine what

00:21:11.170 --> 00:21:12.330
it's like to go to college.

00:21:12.330 --> 00:21:15.450
They might not see
themselves going to college.

00:21:15.450 --> 00:21:18.390
And so we wanted
to enable students

00:21:18.390 --> 00:21:21.070
all over the world to get
excited about college--

00:21:21.070 --> 00:21:25.020
to envision what it's like, to
see how much fun college is,

00:21:25.020 --> 00:21:27.730
not only all the people and the
friendships that you'll make,

00:21:27.730 --> 00:21:30.330
but also all of the
academic opportunities

00:21:30.330 --> 00:21:31.710
that are possible.

00:21:31.710 --> 00:21:35.570
And so being able to visualize
what campus life is like

00:21:35.570 --> 00:21:38.670
helps encourage students
to take that first step

00:21:38.670 --> 00:21:42.510
towards applying for college.

00:21:42.510 --> 00:21:47.420
And similarly, when Soledad
O'Brien saw Expeditions,

00:21:47.420 --> 00:21:52.500
she had a vision for broadening
kids' exposure to careers.

00:21:52.500 --> 00:21:54.650
We know that kids
dream about what they

00:21:54.650 --> 00:21:56.190
want to be when they grow up.

00:21:56.190 --> 00:21:58.000
But those dreams
are often shaped

00:21:58.000 --> 00:22:01.820
by the professional
people in their lives.

00:22:01.820 --> 00:22:04.480
And we know that getting
exposure to careers

00:22:04.480 --> 00:22:05.900
is an important
learning process.

00:22:05.900 --> 00:22:09.050
And this usually happens
through internships.

00:22:09.050 --> 00:22:12.150
But what happens if you
don't have an internship,

00:22:12.150 --> 00:22:15.100
or you don't have
mentors in your life?

00:22:15.100 --> 00:22:19.190
So we've been building a
variety of career expeditions

00:22:19.190 --> 00:22:22.520
to show what it's like and what
professional jobs are out there

00:22:22.520 --> 00:22:24.590
so that students can
explore the day in

00:22:24.590 --> 00:22:26.870
and day out of someone's career.

00:22:26.870 --> 00:22:29.160
They can see what
that person studied.

00:22:29.160 --> 00:22:30.740
They can find out
what they don't

00:22:30.740 --> 00:22:32.740
like about their job,
which is actually a really

00:22:32.740 --> 00:22:34.510
important learning opportunity.

00:22:34.510 --> 00:22:39.770
And we've worked with a number
of professionals, including

00:22:39.770 --> 00:22:42.880
the paleontologist
professor from the American

00:22:42.880 --> 00:22:46.380
Museum of Natural History, and
others like Pam Terrell who's

00:22:46.380 --> 00:22:48.900
an airline pilot for
American Airlines--

00:22:48.900 --> 00:22:51.490
and even an aquarist,
which I didn't even know it

00:22:51.490 --> 00:22:53.990
was a career until we built it.

00:22:53.990 --> 00:22:54.599
You can laugh.

00:22:54.599 --> 00:22:55.098
It's OK.

00:22:57.850 --> 00:23:01.350
And it turns out you learn a
lot when you bring your product

00:23:01.350 --> 00:23:03.310
to 1 million students.

00:23:03.310 --> 00:23:05.950
So I wanted to share
some of those learnings

00:23:05.950 --> 00:23:09.820
that we've experienced
along the way.

00:23:09.820 --> 00:23:14.000
Number 1, we know that teachers
need very specific tools

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:15.920
to do their job well.

00:23:15.920 --> 00:23:18.200
A teacher needs to
be able to direct

00:23:18.200 --> 00:23:20.460
their whole class at once.

00:23:20.460 --> 00:23:24.590
They need to be able to get
their students' attention.

00:23:24.590 --> 00:23:26.450
And they also need to
be able to see what

00:23:26.450 --> 00:23:28.330
their students are working on.

00:23:28.330 --> 00:23:33.300
And this remains
particularly true in VR.

00:23:33.300 --> 00:23:37.680
Teachers aren't experts of
every single place in the world.

00:23:37.680 --> 00:23:41.580
So to make it easy to
direct their class,

00:23:41.580 --> 00:23:45.190
content providers provide
the descriptions and points

00:23:45.190 --> 00:23:47.660
of interests of
particular locations

00:23:47.660 --> 00:23:50.420
so that the teacher doesn't
have to spend all the time

00:23:50.420 --> 00:23:52.760
researching and fact finding.

00:23:52.760 --> 00:23:55.610
So let's take this
panorama for example.

00:23:55.610 --> 00:23:57.750
A teacher in the
US may have never

00:23:57.750 --> 00:24:00.210
visited Buckingham Palace
before and might not

00:24:00.210 --> 00:24:01.860
know that this is
actually the Portrait

00:24:01.860 --> 00:24:04.270
Gallery in Buckingham Palace.

00:24:04.270 --> 00:24:06.790
And so with these descriptions
and points of interest,

00:24:06.790 --> 00:24:09.330
the teacher is able to point
out the famous Canaletto

00:24:09.330 --> 00:24:11.950
painting that's hanging
above the fireplace.

00:24:11.950 --> 00:24:14.310
We wanted to free
teachers' time up so

00:24:14.310 --> 00:24:17.665
they can spend the time
creating engaging lessons

00:24:17.665 --> 00:24:20.690
and incorporate it
into their curriculum,

00:24:20.690 --> 00:24:24.630
not having to research
all these places.

00:24:24.630 --> 00:24:26.620
And when we first
built these tours,

00:24:26.620 --> 00:24:28.760
we assigned a grade
and subject to them.

00:24:28.760 --> 00:24:31.280
We thought it would make it
easier to find the content.

00:24:31.280 --> 00:24:34.600
But what we found was that
the Expeditions were only

00:24:34.600 --> 00:24:38.390
used by those teachers in
those grade and subjects, which

00:24:38.390 --> 00:24:39.910
limited the use of the app.

00:24:39.910 --> 00:24:42.690
And we have over 200
expeditions ranging

00:24:42.690 --> 00:24:45.740
from all kinds of topics.

00:24:45.740 --> 00:24:50.300
And so we decided to remove
those tags for each expedition,

00:24:50.300 --> 00:24:53.380
because what we realized
was that the panoramas don't

00:24:53.380 --> 00:24:54.870
actually change.

00:24:54.870 --> 00:24:57.030
What changes is how
the teacher actually

00:24:57.030 --> 00:25:00.100
applies them to the lesson.

00:25:00.100 --> 00:25:03.300
And the minute we did
that, we saw Expeditions

00:25:03.300 --> 00:25:06.470
used in the most creative way.

00:25:06.470 --> 00:25:10.280
Take, for example, this
expedition of Egypt.

00:25:10.280 --> 00:25:13.840
An elementary math teacher
used this expedition

00:25:13.840 --> 00:25:16.450
to create a lesson
about how to calculate

00:25:16.450 --> 00:25:19.120
the area of a triangle.

00:25:19.120 --> 00:25:20.180
Pretty smart.

00:25:20.180 --> 00:25:23.790
And that same expedition was
used in a high school world

00:25:23.790 --> 00:25:26.980
civilization class to
teach about hieroglyphics

00:25:26.980 --> 00:25:30.680
and how ancient Egyptians
communicated with one another.

00:25:30.680 --> 00:25:34.160
And that same expedition was
used in a college art history

00:25:34.160 --> 00:25:37.020
class to teach about
the art and architecture

00:25:37.020 --> 00:25:39.880
of the Egyptian civilization.

00:25:39.880 --> 00:25:44.170
Now, if that had been labeled an
elementary math lesson or math

00:25:44.170 --> 00:25:47.790
expedition, there is no way that
art history teacher in college

00:25:47.790 --> 00:25:49.310
was going to use that lesson.

00:25:49.310 --> 00:25:53.410
And so that was one of the
key learnings that we had.

00:25:53.410 --> 00:25:56.520
And just like a normal
class, it can sometimes

00:25:56.520 --> 00:25:59.850
be difficult to get
a student's attention

00:25:59.850 --> 00:26:01.750
during the middle of a lesson.

00:26:01.750 --> 00:26:03.540
So imagine that in VR.

00:26:03.540 --> 00:26:07.500
Kids are super-excited about
expeditions and VR in general.

00:26:07.500 --> 00:26:09.720
And so after a few
pilots, we realized

00:26:09.720 --> 00:26:12.650
that we actually needed
to provide a Pause

00:26:12.650 --> 00:26:14.020
button for teachers.

00:26:14.020 --> 00:26:16.320
So when the teacher
hits that Pause button,

00:26:16.320 --> 00:26:17.630
the screen goes black.

00:26:17.630 --> 00:26:20.210
And it says,
"Paused by Teacher."

00:26:20.210 --> 00:26:26.150
And immediately you hear,
awwww, can we go back?

00:26:26.150 --> 00:26:28.970
And instantaneously,
the students

00:26:28.970 --> 00:26:30.210
put down their devices.

00:26:30.210 --> 00:26:34.040
You don't hear the teacher
say, now put down your devices.

00:26:34.040 --> 00:26:35.970
It just happens automatically.

00:26:35.970 --> 00:26:38.120
And the Pause
button is easily one

00:26:38.120 --> 00:26:40.200
of the most important
features for teachers.

00:26:40.200 --> 00:26:42.420
And jokingly, they ask
me if we can add that

00:26:42.420 --> 00:26:43.880
to all of their student devices.

00:26:47.080 --> 00:26:50.190
And we also heard from teachers
that knowing that students are

00:26:50.190 --> 00:26:52.760
engaged is really important.

00:26:52.760 --> 00:26:55.260
The way a teacher knows
if a student is engaged

00:26:55.260 --> 00:26:58.910
is by looking at what they're
doing-- writing something down,

00:26:58.910 --> 00:27:01.450
or looking up at the board.

00:27:01.450 --> 00:27:05.110
And that remains really
important in VR as well.

00:27:05.110 --> 00:27:08.860
But if you think about it,
when you're in your VR viewer,

00:27:08.860 --> 00:27:11.550
the teacher can't see
where you're looking.

00:27:11.550 --> 00:27:12.990
And that was
definitely something

00:27:12.990 --> 00:27:16.260
that was missing from our
app was the student gaze.

00:27:16.260 --> 00:27:19.447
And so we realized that when a
teacher points something out,

00:27:19.447 --> 00:27:21.780
they need to be able to see
if the students are actually

00:27:21.780 --> 00:27:22.521
looking at it.

00:27:22.521 --> 00:27:24.020
So if you look on
the screen, you'll

00:27:24.020 --> 00:27:25.520
see these little smiley faces.

00:27:25.520 --> 00:27:28.680
And those smiley faces represent
the students in a class.

00:27:28.680 --> 00:27:30.920
And so when the teacher
points something out,

00:27:30.920 --> 00:27:33.030
you see this swarm
of smiley faces

00:27:33.030 --> 00:27:35.080
to that point of interest.

00:27:35.080 --> 00:27:37.520
Well, if that swarm
doesn't appear,

00:27:37.520 --> 00:27:40.240
and you see students
looking all over the place,

00:27:40.240 --> 00:27:42.600
you know that you might need
to use that Pause button

00:27:42.600 --> 00:27:43.690
and refocus the class.

00:27:46.952 --> 00:27:48.410
The other thing
that we learned was

00:27:48.410 --> 00:27:52.670
that VR and Expeditions empowers
students to be teachers.

00:27:55.820 --> 00:27:57.680
Teachers don't have
all the answers.

00:27:57.680 --> 00:27:59.950
And instead of having all
the answers, what we found

00:27:59.950 --> 00:28:03.070
is that the teachers really
serve as a facilitator.

00:28:03.070 --> 00:28:05.080
They build upon
what the students

00:28:05.080 --> 00:28:10.580
are seeing and exploring
from panorama to panorama.

00:28:10.580 --> 00:28:12.760
And across the world,
we saw this thing

00:28:12.760 --> 00:28:15.110
happening where teachers
would ask their students

00:28:15.110 --> 00:28:19.260
to explore a panorama, find
something interesting, and then

00:28:19.260 --> 00:28:21.890
would invite a handful
of the students up

00:28:21.890 --> 00:28:24.370
and actually point out that
thing that they thought

00:28:24.370 --> 00:28:25.920
was interesting
and talk about it,

00:28:25.920 --> 00:28:28.640
and share it with the
rest of their class.

00:28:28.640 --> 00:28:31.900
And this is exactly what
Seymour Papert was talking about

00:28:31.900 --> 00:28:33.930
in the quote that
Ben referenced,

00:28:33.930 --> 00:28:36.330
that the role of the
teacher is to create

00:28:36.330 --> 00:28:39.750
the conditions for invention
rather than provide

00:28:39.750 --> 00:28:41.540
ready-made knowledge.

00:28:41.540 --> 00:28:43.740
And interaction
is really critical

00:28:43.740 --> 00:28:45.126
to add to this experience.

00:28:45.126 --> 00:28:47.250
And it's something that we
know we need to continue

00:28:47.250 --> 00:28:51.000
to add to in Expeditions.

00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:53.640
And we also know
that learning happens

00:28:53.640 --> 00:28:54.790
outside of the classroom.

00:28:54.790 --> 00:28:57.830
Many of us would say that
we're lifelong learners.

00:28:57.830 --> 00:29:00.780
And as it turns
out, Expeditions can

00:29:00.780 --> 00:29:03.900
be used for a broad range
of learning opportunities

00:29:03.900 --> 00:29:05.230
beyond the classroom.

00:29:05.230 --> 00:29:08.570
We've actually been piloting
Expeditions in senior citizen

00:29:08.570 --> 00:29:11.010
homes and children's hospitals.

00:29:11.010 --> 00:29:14.630
And the feedback as well
has been incredible.

00:29:14.630 --> 00:29:16.940
We have lots of requests
from senior citizens

00:29:16.940 --> 00:29:20.540
to go and visit Verona,
Italy to see the setting

00:29:20.540 --> 00:29:22.460
of Romeo and Juliet.

00:29:22.460 --> 00:29:26.660
And a lot of kids and
children's hospitals

00:29:26.660 --> 00:29:29.010
have been asking
to go underwater.

00:29:29.010 --> 00:29:32.060
All they want to do is pick up
the goggles, hold their breath,

00:29:32.060 --> 00:29:36.540
go underwater, and explore the
majestic Great Barrier Reef.

00:29:36.540 --> 00:29:38.940
And for that moment,
those kids are

00:29:38.940 --> 00:29:40.720
forgetting about their illness.

00:29:40.720 --> 00:29:42.000
They're smiling.

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:42.960
They're laughing.

00:29:42.960 --> 00:29:45.990
And they're asking questions
about what they're seeing

00:29:45.990 --> 00:29:48.870
and what they're learning.

00:29:48.870 --> 00:29:50.650
So now I'd like to
turn it over to Ben

00:29:50.650 --> 00:29:54.314
to talk about group
learning in Expeditions.

00:29:54.314 --> 00:29:56.258
[APPLAUSE]

00:29:59.077 --> 00:30:00.910
BEN SCHROM: So one of
things that we've seen

00:30:00.910 --> 00:30:03.445
is that one of the primary
features of school-- I

00:30:03.445 --> 00:30:05.320
didn't love going to
school when I was a kid.

00:30:05.320 --> 00:30:06.580
But one of the
things you realize

00:30:06.580 --> 00:30:08.163
is that group learning
is actually one

00:30:08.163 --> 00:30:09.910
of the best features of school.

00:30:09.910 --> 00:30:11.370
An early decision
that we made was

00:30:11.370 --> 00:30:14.580
to make Expeditions
fundamentally social.

00:30:14.580 --> 00:30:16.360
And many of the
teachers we talked to,

00:30:16.360 --> 00:30:18.690
even the ones who had never
seen the cardboard, who

00:30:18.690 --> 00:30:21.830
thought Oculus Rift was
like a geological phenomena,

00:30:21.830 --> 00:30:26.550
they carried this preconceived
notion that VR was a singular,

00:30:26.550 --> 00:30:28.420
isolated activity.

00:30:28.420 --> 00:30:31.020
So we took steps from the
get-go to make it social,

00:30:31.020 --> 00:30:33.890
something you do with a group
like an actual expedition.

00:30:33.890 --> 00:30:36.230
It's not a canned
experience as a result.

00:30:36.230 --> 00:30:37.240
Every time is different.

00:30:37.240 --> 00:30:39.490
It's a dynamic experience
where your teachers

00:30:39.490 --> 00:30:41.050
and your classmates
are the ones who

00:30:41.050 --> 00:30:43.650
are asking questions, making
comments, and pointing things

00:30:43.650 --> 00:30:45.340
out.

00:30:45.340 --> 00:30:47.060
Though I've seen
some great uses of VR

00:30:47.060 --> 00:30:49.435
to provide singular focus,
it's really, really important,

00:30:49.435 --> 00:30:51.101
I think, for us as a
community of people

00:30:51.101 --> 00:30:53.710
who are beginning to build up
this technology, to counteract

00:30:53.710 --> 00:30:55.930
this notion that VR
is a fundamentally

00:30:55.930 --> 00:30:57.404
isolated experience.

00:30:57.404 --> 00:30:59.070
If you're not convinced
of that, there's

00:30:59.070 --> 00:31:00.486
a good example
from history, which

00:31:00.486 --> 00:31:03.900
was Edison's first attempt at
the camera, the Kinetoscope.

00:31:03.900 --> 00:31:06.530
Edison assumed that movies
would turn out to be something

00:31:06.530 --> 00:31:08.070
that you just watched alone.

00:31:08.070 --> 00:31:10.540
And he resisted projecting
movies onto a screen

00:31:10.540 --> 00:31:13.500
so that a bunch of people
could watch at the same time.

00:31:13.500 --> 00:31:15.430
We all know how that turned out.

00:31:15.430 --> 00:31:19.800
So lots of signals that VR
is super, super important

00:31:19.800 --> 00:31:22.437
to have a social element to it.

00:31:22.437 --> 00:31:24.770
Another key point, and this
is certainly true, basically

00:31:24.770 --> 00:31:26.186
for all technology,
but especially

00:31:26.186 --> 00:31:28.240
for educational
technology, is that making

00:31:28.240 --> 00:31:30.870
it simple and easy and
especially quick to get going

00:31:30.870 --> 00:31:32.350
is really critical.

00:31:32.350 --> 00:31:35.330
I remember reading about there's
some warehouse, in Florida

00:31:35.330 --> 00:31:37.950
of all places, that
the Air Force can

00:31:37.950 --> 00:31:41.800
make super, super cold
like subzero temperatures.

00:31:41.800 --> 00:31:45.140
And they put planes in that to
test them before they actually

00:31:45.140 --> 00:31:46.550
put them into high altitude.

00:31:46.550 --> 00:31:48.870
Classrooms are like that
subzero warehouse, right?

00:31:48.870 --> 00:31:52.080
They are very harsh environments
in which to deploy technology.

00:31:52.080 --> 00:31:55.689
And it needs to be simple
and robust, or it will fail.

00:31:55.689 --> 00:31:57.480
So we found that most
teachers are actually

00:31:57.480 --> 00:31:59.720
really skeptical that they could
even use VR in the classroom,

00:31:59.720 --> 00:32:01.230
not because they couldn't
figure out how to use,

00:32:01.230 --> 00:32:03.327
but because they were
really intimidated by it,

00:32:03.327 --> 00:32:05.660
because they thought would
be too complicated to set up,

00:32:05.660 --> 00:32:07.576
because they thought it
would be a distraction

00:32:07.576 --> 00:32:08.530
for their students.

00:32:08.530 --> 00:32:11.470
So we were super-committed
to ensuring that teachers who

00:32:11.470 --> 00:32:14.670
hated tech loved Expeditions.

00:32:14.670 --> 00:32:16.870
And the best way to do
that was to make it simple.

00:32:16.870 --> 00:32:18.820
We found that time
and time again.

00:32:18.820 --> 00:32:22.020
It's almost defined by
how few features it has.

00:32:22.020 --> 00:32:23.800
It doesn't require
an account login.

00:32:23.800 --> 00:32:25.260
And we wanted to
counteract as many

00:32:25.260 --> 00:32:26.690
of the technological
prerequisites

00:32:26.690 --> 00:32:28.340
as we possibly could.

00:32:28.340 --> 00:32:31.400
So we made sure that it worked
well in devices that classrooms

00:32:31.400 --> 00:32:33.139
already had like tablets.

00:32:33.139 --> 00:32:34.930
You don't need a
Cardboard viewer to do it.

00:32:34.930 --> 00:32:36.150
You can do it what
we call magic window

00:32:36.150 --> 00:32:37.620
mode where you look in 2D.

00:32:37.620 --> 00:32:40.282
And if you've never used VR,
if you've never used Cardboard,

00:32:40.282 --> 00:32:42.740
that's actually a really, really
magical amazing experience

00:32:42.740 --> 00:32:44.500
by itself.

00:32:44.500 --> 00:32:46.190
Another challenge
we encountered was

00:32:46.190 --> 00:32:49.160
that getting Expeditions to
work in environments with little

00:32:49.160 --> 00:32:51.860
to no internet connectivity
was really challenging.

00:32:51.860 --> 00:32:53.380
And that's a very
common scenario

00:32:53.380 --> 00:32:58.930
not just in affluent schools,
but in disadvantaged schools.

00:32:58.930 --> 00:33:02.347
Many, many schools do not
have the network environment

00:33:02.347 --> 00:33:04.430
that would allow them to
pull these super-large VR

00:33:04.430 --> 00:33:08.146
assets down out of the
cloud 30 devices at a time.

00:33:08.146 --> 00:33:10.870
And we decided we couldn't
wait for Google Fiber.

00:33:10.870 --> 00:33:13.030
So we built Expeditions
to work without the need

00:33:13.030 --> 00:33:14.360
for the internet.

00:33:14.360 --> 00:33:16.300
Basically, the
guide's device-- that

00:33:16.300 --> 00:33:17.960
tablet that the
teacher is holding--

00:33:17.960 --> 00:33:20.090
operates as a local server.

00:33:20.090 --> 00:33:22.590
And it serves imagery to each
of the connected clients, each

00:33:22.590 --> 00:33:25.560
of the devices in Cardboard,
over the local Wi-Fi network.

00:33:25.560 --> 00:33:27.730
So as long as that tablet
has cached the imagery

00:33:27.730 --> 00:33:29.760
from the internet at
some point before,

00:33:29.760 --> 00:33:32.110
it works without the
internet, which means

00:33:32.110 --> 00:33:33.390
we can take this anywhere.

00:33:33.390 --> 00:33:34.390
We can take it to Ghana.

00:33:34.390 --> 00:33:35.820
We can take it to
the rural Amazon.

00:33:35.820 --> 00:33:37.236
We can take it all
over the place.

00:33:39.620 --> 00:33:41.080
This is another one.

00:33:41.080 --> 00:33:43.620
Getting beyond this wow moment.

00:33:43.620 --> 00:33:46.790
Obviously, we love these
moments when students first

00:33:46.790 --> 00:33:47.820
experience Expeditions.

00:33:47.820 --> 00:33:51.200
And you saw that in the
video with Lance's class.

00:33:51.200 --> 00:33:52.870
Basically, any
chance to see someone

00:33:52.870 --> 00:33:55.730
experiencing VR for the first
time is a pretty magical one.

00:33:55.730 --> 00:33:57.620
It's an amazing moment.

00:33:57.620 --> 00:34:01.940
But the sort of immersion and
engagement that VR provides

00:34:01.940 --> 00:34:04.800
is a bit of a moving target.

00:34:04.800 --> 00:34:06.650
What we consider
mindblowingly immersive

00:34:06.650 --> 00:34:09.090
right now will be
considered table stakes

00:34:09.090 --> 00:34:12.030
at some point in the
not too distant future.

00:34:12.030 --> 00:34:13.879
And we should be
excited that technology

00:34:13.879 --> 00:34:15.670
will continue to push
the boundaries of how

00:34:15.670 --> 00:34:17.929
immersive VR can become.

00:34:17.929 --> 00:34:20.920
So you should be really
careful to rely too much

00:34:20.920 --> 00:34:23.330
on the initial moment of
sort of awe and wonder

00:34:23.330 --> 00:34:25.400
that comes from first use.

00:34:25.400 --> 00:34:28.210
It won't ultimately
mask poor designs.

00:34:28.210 --> 00:34:29.880
And it might
actually distract you

00:34:29.880 --> 00:34:32.719
from realizing design
flaws for a long time.

00:34:32.719 --> 00:34:35.090
A good piece of VR
learning technology

00:34:35.090 --> 00:34:37.639
still needs to be
actually fulfilling

00:34:37.639 --> 00:34:39.540
its fundamental
learning objectives.

00:34:39.540 --> 00:34:42.989
It's not just about being fun,
or immersive, or engaging.

00:34:42.989 --> 00:34:45.280
Measuring it can be really,
really hard at first.

00:34:45.280 --> 00:34:48.170
But don't start entirely
trusting your feedback

00:34:48.170 --> 00:34:50.860
until your users have been
able to use it for a few hours,

00:34:50.860 --> 00:34:52.929
or better yet, a
few days or weeks.

00:34:52.929 --> 00:34:56.440
Get feedback, iterate,
ship it, do it a lot,

00:34:56.440 --> 00:34:58.400
like basically
fundamental technology,

00:34:58.400 --> 00:35:00.670
but super, super
important for VR.

00:35:00.670 --> 00:35:02.540
As Jen mentioned, this
is one of the reasons

00:35:02.540 --> 00:35:05.850
that we embarked on
the Pioneer Program.

00:35:05.850 --> 00:35:07.350
So hopefully we've
seen a little bit

00:35:07.350 --> 00:35:09.808
how we think Expeditions can
transform the classroom today.

00:35:09.808 --> 00:35:12.200
But we're really, really
excited about the possibility

00:35:12.200 --> 00:35:14.110
of more advanced VR
in the classroom.

00:35:14.110 --> 00:35:17.559
And to talk a little bit about
that, I'd like to invite Rob.

00:35:17.559 --> 00:35:19.026
[APPLAUSE]

