00:36:06.830 --> 00:36:08.110
of how evolution is portrayed.

00:36:08.110 --> 00:36:09.930
You can think of
it as this forward

00:36:09.930 --> 00:36:11.660
moving intention direction.

00:36:11.660 --> 00:36:14.200
But that's not what evolution
looks like in species.

00:36:14.200 --> 00:36:17.890
And it's not what it looks like
in any other technology either.

00:36:17.890 --> 00:36:19.571
In any evolutionary
process, we know

00:36:19.571 --> 00:36:21.820
that there are going to be
false starts and dead ends.

00:36:21.820 --> 00:36:23.600
And that's why within
the Daydream team,

00:36:23.600 --> 00:36:27.660
we're spending our time on these
things called Daydream Labs.

00:36:27.660 --> 00:36:30.130
Put bluntly, even
here at Google,

00:36:30.130 --> 00:36:34.037
we really know that we don't
know very much about VR yet.

00:36:34.037 --> 00:36:36.120
So we're looking at highly
experimental ideas that

00:36:36.120 --> 00:36:38.090
push the boundary
of VR, force us

00:36:38.090 --> 00:36:39.599
to reconsider what's possible.

00:36:39.599 --> 00:36:41.390
And we're exploring
this vast new territory

00:36:41.390 --> 00:36:43.500
right alongside you.

00:36:43.500 --> 00:36:45.400
We've gone back to
first principles.

00:36:45.400 --> 00:36:46.880
And we've tried
to set aside what

00:36:46.880 --> 00:36:49.480
we think we know about
education and app design,

00:36:49.480 --> 00:36:51.320
because the best
VR experiences out

00:36:51.320 --> 00:36:56.110
there aren't going to be other
forms of media pulled into VR

00:36:56.110 --> 00:36:57.102
and re-imagined in VR.

00:36:57.102 --> 00:36:58.810
They're going to be
built from the ground

00:36:58.810 --> 00:37:01.790
up in a way that really
understands the strengths

00:37:01.790 --> 00:37:03.090
and weaknesses of VR.

00:37:03.090 --> 00:37:04.630
And in the near
future, like I said,

00:37:04.630 --> 00:37:07.510
I hope we're going to see
entirely new categories of VR

00:37:07.510 --> 00:37:08.987
educational experiences.

00:37:08.987 --> 00:37:11.070
Now, since we started this
prototyping experiment,

00:37:11.070 --> 00:37:12.790
we've built more
than 60 prototypes

00:37:12.790 --> 00:37:16.796
that cover of a huge
array of use cases.

00:37:16.796 --> 00:37:18.420
So I want to cover
just a few of those.

00:37:18.420 --> 00:37:20.300
And this isn't just
to show off our work.

00:37:20.300 --> 00:37:22.360
Hopefully, by seeing
some of these examples,

00:37:22.360 --> 00:37:24.479
it'll spark ideas
in your own minds.

00:37:24.479 --> 00:37:26.770
If you're curious to learn
more about these prototypes,

00:37:26.770 --> 00:37:28.690
there are two talks that
took place yesterday.

00:37:28.690 --> 00:37:31.420
One is called,
"Daydream Labs-- Lessons

00:37:31.420 --> 00:37:33.000
Learned from VR Prototyping."

00:37:33.000 --> 00:37:35.350
The second talk is called,
"VR Design Process-- Turning

00:37:35.350 --> 00:37:36.540
Fantasy Into Reality."

00:37:36.540 --> 00:37:38.530
They're both already
available on YouTube.

00:37:38.530 --> 00:37:40.530
But for now, I want to
focus on these prototypes

00:37:40.530 --> 00:37:44.200
that we think can really have
the power to change education.

00:37:44.200 --> 00:37:46.240
What we're looking at
here is a molecule viewer.

00:37:46.240 --> 00:37:49.830
And so much of what we explore
in education is at a scale

00:37:49.830 --> 00:37:52.030
that almost completely
defies comprehension.

00:37:52.030 --> 00:37:53.840
From atoms and
molecules all the way up

00:37:53.840 --> 00:37:56.670
to galaxies and superclusters,
pictures in textbooks

00:37:56.670 --> 00:37:59.270
just don't get us excited
about this content.

00:37:59.270 --> 00:38:02.050
But what if you could hold
that molecule in your hand?

00:38:02.050 --> 00:38:03.750
And the app that
I'm showing here

00:38:03.750 --> 00:38:06.100
doesn't just have a couple
of molecules in its database.

00:38:06.100 --> 00:38:08.090
It has an enormous collection.

00:38:08.090 --> 00:38:10.940
And it builds the model of
the molecule dynamically

00:38:10.940 --> 00:38:13.190
based on what it knows about
the chemical composition.

00:38:13.190 --> 00:38:15.273
I don't know if you're
familiar with this molecule

00:38:15.273 --> 00:38:16.002
in particular.

00:38:16.002 --> 00:38:20.795
It's one of the foundations of
life as we know it-- caffeine.

00:38:20.795 --> 00:38:23.407
So now let's go 31
orders of magnitude

00:38:23.407 --> 00:38:25.740
in the other direction and
take a look at the Milky Way.

00:38:25.740 --> 00:38:27.220
Here we see our VR planetarium.

00:38:27.220 --> 00:38:30.010
And real planetariums
are amazing.

00:38:30.010 --> 00:38:31.599
But here you're in control.

00:38:31.599 --> 00:38:33.390
You can pull a
constellation from the night

00:38:33.390 --> 00:38:36.500
sky-- pull it right in front
of you to get more information.

00:38:36.500 --> 00:38:38.380
Next up, biology lab.

00:38:38.380 --> 00:38:40.710
Here what we tell the
student is that you're

00:38:40.710 --> 00:38:42.530
an explorer from an
alien civilization

00:38:42.530 --> 00:38:43.830
in the distant future.

00:38:43.830 --> 00:38:46.431
And you've stumbled
upon this skeleton.

00:38:46.431 --> 00:38:48.680
And you're trying to learn
as much as you can about it

00:38:48.680 --> 00:38:51.280
by assembling the bones
into a human form.

00:38:51.280 --> 00:38:54.410
So a careful observer will see
the different types of joints.

00:38:54.410 --> 00:38:56.830
She'll notice that when slender
bones are paired together,

00:38:56.830 --> 00:38:59.038
those are the ones that go
the farthest from the body

00:38:59.038 --> 00:39:00.500
on the arms and the legs.

00:39:00.500 --> 00:39:03.070
Hovering labels tell you that
this is the radius and ulna

00:39:03.070 --> 00:39:04.420
or the tibia and fibula.

00:39:04.420 --> 00:39:06.530
And all of these
clues give you insight

00:39:06.530 --> 00:39:09.230
into the human body in a way
that a textbook really never

00:39:09.230 --> 00:39:11.040
could.

00:39:11.040 --> 00:39:12.020
Here's our physics lab.

00:39:12.020 --> 00:39:14.190
And the key here is that
there are two players

00:39:14.190 --> 00:39:15.950
in the same virtual space.

00:39:15.950 --> 00:39:18.450
Ben was talking about
how participating

00:39:18.450 --> 00:39:21.450
together and having us
be social is important.

00:39:21.450 --> 00:39:23.692
And these two players in
the same virtual space

00:39:23.692 --> 00:39:25.150
could be in the
same physical room.

00:39:25.150 --> 00:39:27.390
Or they could be across
the globe from each other.

00:39:27.390 --> 00:39:29.754
Either can change the physics
parameters of the scene

00:39:29.754 --> 00:39:31.170
like the mass of
the bowling ball.

00:39:31.170 --> 00:39:32.910
And the objective
is to set the values

00:39:32.910 --> 00:39:36.220
just right so that the bowling
ball knocks over the pin.

00:39:36.220 --> 00:39:38.790
And being able to share
this experience really

00:39:38.790 --> 00:39:40.910
amplifies the fun.

00:39:40.910 --> 00:39:42.140
Next up is language learning.

00:39:42.140 --> 00:39:44.994
And this is such a perfect
example for virtual reality.

00:39:44.994 --> 00:39:46.410
It builds on
techniques that we've

00:39:46.410 --> 00:39:48.250
been using in
conversational instruction

00:39:48.250 --> 00:39:50.730
to put you directly
into the conversation.

00:39:50.730 --> 00:39:52.566
And in this video, we've
turned on subtitles

00:39:52.566 --> 00:39:54.190
to help you understand
what's going on.

00:39:54.190 --> 00:39:55.939
But if you've taken
the time to just learn

00:39:55.939 --> 00:39:57.990
a few words in one of
the previous sections

00:39:57.990 --> 00:40:00.199
of this educational
app, you have no trouble

00:40:00.199 --> 00:40:02.240
participating in this
conversation with these two

00:40:02.240 --> 00:40:03.750
young girls.

00:40:03.750 --> 00:40:05.845
In this case, VR
does more than just

00:40:05.845 --> 00:40:07.970
make you feel like you're
part of the conversation.

00:40:07.970 --> 00:40:09.030
It does that very well.

00:40:09.030 --> 00:40:11.800
But it also removes distraction
so that you can really

00:40:11.800 --> 00:40:14.515
focus on the lesson.

00:40:14.515 --> 00:40:16.140
Now, when we're
talking about learning,

00:40:16.140 --> 00:40:17.598
sometimes we just
think about kids.

00:40:17.598 --> 00:40:20.030
But really, learning
is a lifelong process--

00:40:20.030 --> 00:40:23.220
professional skills, job
retraining-- how about a skill

00:40:23.220 --> 00:40:26.040
that terrifies most adults,
doing what we're doing up

00:40:26.040 --> 00:40:27.270
here-- public speaking.

00:40:27.270 --> 00:40:29.580
What if you could prepare
your talk by presenting

00:40:29.580 --> 00:40:31.380
to a simulated audience?

00:40:31.380 --> 00:40:33.960
We've seen VR used to
help overcome phobias.

00:40:33.960 --> 00:40:35.721
And this isn't really
that different.

00:40:35.721 --> 00:40:37.970
Public speaking is really
uncomfortable for people who

00:40:37.970 --> 00:40:39.530
don't have experience at it.

00:40:39.530 --> 00:40:42.560
But in VR, you can simulate
that stressful environment

00:40:42.560 --> 00:40:44.792
without fear of judgment
from a real audience.

00:40:44.792 --> 00:40:47.250
So that's kind of handy.

00:40:47.250 --> 00:40:49.440
Now, let's change pace a
lot and go back to the days

00:40:49.440 --> 00:40:54.200
before Google and talk about
the arc of educational games.

00:40:54.200 --> 00:40:57.690
So how many people
here died of dysentery?

00:40:57.690 --> 00:41:01.130
Not as many as I thought, but
a third of the audience here.

00:41:01.130 --> 00:41:03.860
Personally, I see "Oregon
Trail" as actually leading

00:41:03.860 --> 00:41:05.970
a revolution in
educational games,

00:41:05.970 --> 00:41:07.230
because it was so different.

00:41:07.230 --> 00:41:09.020
It wasn't just a
wrapper around a bunch

00:41:09.020 --> 00:41:11.440
of boring educational content.

00:41:11.440 --> 00:41:13.600
Kids can see right through that.

00:41:13.600 --> 00:41:16.350
And I see a lot of educational
games where kids get

00:41:16.350 --> 00:41:18.860
spoonfed a bunch of facts,
and then they answer a quiz.

00:41:18.860 --> 00:41:21.570
And this almost teaches
them-- it almost

00:41:21.570 --> 00:41:23.060
reinforces that learning sucks.

00:41:23.060 --> 00:41:24.890
But if you do it,
you get this reward

00:41:24.890 --> 00:41:26.065
of the mini game at the end.

00:41:26.065 --> 00:41:27.440
This isn't what
we want to teach.

00:41:27.440 --> 00:41:29.785
And "Oregon Trail" took a
really different approach.

00:41:29.785 --> 00:41:31.660
It didn't try to feed
you this list of facts.

00:41:31.660 --> 00:41:35.410
It tried to put you in the
shoes of early American pioneers

00:41:35.410 --> 00:41:38.210
so that you can empathize
with the difficulty

00:41:38.210 --> 00:41:39.330
of their journey.

00:41:39.330 --> 00:41:41.080
And this word empathy
is really important,

00:41:41.080 --> 00:41:43.536
because it's something
that VR does really well.

00:41:43.536 --> 00:41:44.910
And at the end of
the experience,

00:41:44.910 --> 00:41:47.118
maybe you don't remember
how long the Oregon Trail is

00:41:47.118 --> 00:41:49.570
or what percentage of
travelers died of dysentery.

00:41:49.570 --> 00:41:52.290
But you understand that it
was a brutal experience.

00:41:52.290 --> 00:41:54.930
And because of that, the people
who undertook that journey

00:41:54.930 --> 00:41:58.370
must have been willing
to shoulder a lot of risk

00:41:58.370 --> 00:42:00.150
in search for a better life.

00:42:00.150 --> 00:42:03.020
Now, today I think this kind
of experience is really hard.

00:42:03.020 --> 00:42:05.710
It has a lot trouble for this
kind of game making inroads

00:42:05.710 --> 00:42:09.050
in education, because
it's not easy to measure

00:42:09.050 --> 00:42:10.192
what the child learns.

00:42:10.192 --> 00:42:11.650
And if you can't
prove that they're

00:42:11.650 --> 00:42:13.775
going to do better on
the test, it kind of

00:42:13.775 --> 00:42:14.900
looks like a waste of time.

00:42:14.900 --> 00:42:16.441
And now you might
really want to come

00:42:16.441 --> 00:42:18.610
to the defense of this piece
of childhood nostalgia.

00:42:18.610 --> 00:42:20.560
But the critics really
have a point here.

00:42:20.560 --> 00:42:23.829
How do you measure the value
of empathy-based education?

00:42:23.829 --> 00:42:26.120
And if you think "Oregon
Trail" was on the right track,

00:42:26.120 --> 00:42:27.661
I think you'll agree
VR has potential

00:42:27.661 --> 00:42:28.980
to really revolutionize this.

00:42:28.980 --> 00:42:30.800
But it's not going to be easy.

00:42:30.800 --> 00:42:33.170
Let's talk a little bit about
what the ingredients are

00:42:33.170 --> 00:42:35.150
that we're going
to need to create

00:42:35.150 --> 00:42:37.361
great immersive
educational experiences.

00:42:37.361 --> 00:42:39.360
And the three components
that I want to focus on

00:42:39.360 --> 00:42:41.200
are these-- immersion,
interactivity,

00:42:41.200 --> 00:42:42.830
and measured results.

00:42:42.830 --> 00:42:45.530
That third one might
come as a surprise.

00:42:45.530 --> 00:42:47.500
Immersion is where
VR really shines.

00:42:47.500 --> 00:42:49.380
It's really hard to make
a VR experience that

00:42:49.380 --> 00:42:50.360
isn't immersive.

00:42:50.360 --> 00:42:52.710
In this example here,
even though the avatars

00:42:52.710 --> 00:42:54.360
are very simple and
cartoonish, when

00:42:54.360 --> 00:42:56.780
you put that headset
on and those little two

00:42:56.780 --> 00:42:58.955
cartoony little girls
turn to face you,

00:42:58.955 --> 00:43:01.036
you want to respond to them.

00:43:01.036 --> 00:43:02.910
They have included you
in their conversation.

00:43:02.910 --> 00:43:04.990
And you don't
hesitate to respond.

00:43:04.990 --> 00:43:06.240
Then we have interactivity.

00:43:06.240 --> 00:43:09.072
Now, Expeditions, like
most classroom experiences,

00:43:09.072 --> 00:43:10.780
is interactive in the
sense that kids can

00:43:10.780 --> 00:43:12.370
look around and ask questions.

00:43:12.370 --> 00:43:13.920
But ultimately,
the teacher drives

00:43:13.920 --> 00:43:15.105
the content and the pace.

00:43:15.105 --> 00:43:16.730
And that works very
well in classrooms.

00:43:16.730 --> 00:43:18.690
But what if we want
a VR experience

00:43:18.690 --> 00:43:21.170
that someone can explore on
their own-- on their own pace,

00:43:21.170 --> 00:43:22.249
on their own time.

00:43:22.249 --> 00:43:24.040
And in this case, adding
more opportunities

00:43:24.040 --> 00:43:25.539
for the viewer to
drive the show can

00:43:25.539 --> 00:43:27.690
do a lot to make the
material more engaging.

00:43:27.690 --> 00:43:29.900
In this two-player
physics lesson example,

00:43:29.900 --> 00:43:32.150
the students have complete
control over the difficulty

00:43:32.150 --> 00:43:33.420
level that they choose.

00:43:33.420 --> 00:43:36.122
And they're also solving
the puzzle themselves.

00:43:36.122 --> 00:43:37.580
And solving that
puzzle on your own

00:43:37.580 --> 00:43:39.705
is a lot more rewarding
than watching somebody else

00:43:39.705 --> 00:43:42.031
do it or talk you through it.

00:43:42.031 --> 00:43:43.030
So here's the tough one.

00:43:43.030 --> 00:43:45.690
Finally, it's important that we
measure how students interact

00:43:45.690 --> 00:43:47.022
with the VR experience.

00:43:47.022 --> 00:43:49.230
It's hugely rewarding to
peek into a classroom that's

00:43:49.230 --> 00:43:51.520
doing a Google Expedition,
whether it's kids or adults,

00:43:51.520 --> 00:43:53.186
and see all those
giggling faces as they

00:43:53.186 --> 00:43:54.930
travel around the world.

00:43:54.930 --> 00:43:58.670
But in order for VR to make
real inroads in education,

00:43:58.670 --> 00:44:01.560
the subjective evaluation
is not going to be enough.

00:44:01.560 --> 00:44:04.520
We need some way to measure how
students interact with the app

00:44:04.520 --> 00:44:06.920
and demonstrate the resulting
knowledge of a subject.

00:44:06.920 --> 00:44:08.680
And I'm not going to
pretend that this is easy.

00:44:08.680 --> 00:44:10.555
People have been trying
this for a long time.

00:44:10.555 --> 00:44:13.080
And it's really hard.

00:44:13.080 --> 00:44:15.900
Just choosing an
appropriate metric is hard,

00:44:15.900 --> 00:44:18.110
and then measuring those
aspects without turning

00:44:18.110 --> 00:44:20.630
your application into a
boring quiz is even harder.

00:44:20.630 --> 00:44:22.670
I think we're going to
need to rethink both

00:44:22.670 --> 00:44:25.790
what we're measuring and
how we're measuring it

00:44:25.790 --> 00:44:27.320
for these things
to move forward.

00:44:27.320 --> 00:44:29.320
And this is why to some
degree these aspects are

00:44:29.320 --> 00:44:30.610
in conflict with each other.

00:44:30.610 --> 00:44:32.690
I can make an experience
that's more immersive.

00:44:32.690 --> 00:44:34.470
But it's hard to
measure the impact.

00:44:34.470 --> 00:44:38.110
I can measure the impact
by forcing students

00:44:38.110 --> 00:44:39.350
to answer trivia questions.

00:44:39.350 --> 00:44:41.550
But all of a sudden, it's
not immersive anymore.

00:44:41.550 --> 00:44:43.310
So it's going to take a
lot of specialized skills

00:44:43.310 --> 00:44:44.060
to get this right.

00:44:44.060 --> 00:44:45.830
And those specialized
skills are going

00:44:45.830 --> 00:44:47.730
to come from specific people.

00:44:47.730 --> 00:44:51.340
And I am going to run
through each of these here.

00:44:51.340 --> 00:44:53.090
The first one, of
course, is teachers.

00:44:53.090 --> 00:44:54.620
Teachers understand
their students.

00:44:54.620 --> 00:44:56.460
And they can't be
excluded from this process

00:44:56.460 --> 00:44:58.477
in creating these
VR applications.

00:44:58.477 --> 00:45:00.060
They need the
flexibility to make sure

00:45:00.060 --> 00:45:03.880
that the VR experience is tuned
to the ability and the style

00:45:03.880 --> 00:45:06.070
of teaching needed
for their classroom.

00:45:06.070 --> 00:45:07.864
Next up, of course,
VR designers--

00:45:07.864 --> 00:45:09.780
they know how to make
an immersive experience.

00:45:09.780 --> 00:45:12.500
And even within this
group, I'm glossing over

00:45:12.500 --> 00:45:14.180
a lot of talent that's needed.

00:45:14.180 --> 00:45:16.880
You need to understand 3D
modeling, interaction design,

00:45:16.880 --> 00:45:18.750
audio design,
environment layout.

00:45:18.750 --> 00:45:21.190
You need to stand understand
what types of motion

00:45:21.190 --> 00:45:22.900
makes people sick.

00:45:22.900 --> 00:45:24.640
It's really a complicated thing.

00:45:24.640 --> 00:45:26.332
Then we have our
classic game designers.

00:45:26.332 --> 00:45:28.040
These people know how
to make experiences

00:45:28.040 --> 00:45:30.600
that are interactive and
sticky and elicit the desired

00:45:30.600 --> 00:45:31.822
behavior.

00:45:31.822 --> 00:45:33.280
Next up, and this
is the one that I

00:45:33.280 --> 00:45:35.910
think is being excluded
too much in this process,

00:45:35.910 --> 00:45:38.345
researchers understand
the metrics of education.

00:45:38.345 --> 00:45:39.720
Now, you might
have heard it said

00:45:39.720 --> 00:45:43.110
before-- if you can't measure
it, you can't improve it.

00:45:43.110 --> 00:45:45.570
In the context of getting
your app out there to schools

00:45:45.570 --> 00:45:48.570
and really getting impact
there, the more apt expression

00:45:48.570 --> 00:45:51.430
might be, if you can't
measure student improvement,

00:45:51.430 --> 00:45:54.227
your app will be discontinued.

00:45:54.227 --> 00:45:56.310
And the final element in
the equation is students.

00:45:56.310 --> 00:45:58.026
Thankfully, this is
a really easy one.

00:45:58.026 --> 00:45:59.400
The students are
the ones who are

00:45:59.400 --> 00:46:01.480
the most open to new
ideas in education,

00:46:01.480 --> 00:46:03.938
because you don't see a fourth
grader come home from school

00:46:03.938 --> 00:46:06.712
and say, mom, I'm not convinced
that this new curriculum

00:46:06.712 --> 00:46:09.170
is adequately fulfilling the
pillars of the next generation

00:46:09.170 --> 00:46:10.730
science standards.

00:46:10.730 --> 00:46:12.135
They say, we went to Europa.

00:46:12.135 --> 00:46:14.260
Did you even know that
Europa is a moon of Jupiter.

00:46:14.260 --> 00:46:16.093
And it's entirely covered
in a frozen ocean.

00:46:16.093 --> 00:46:18.451
How amazing is that?

00:46:18.451 --> 00:46:19.950
So I've talked about
the ingredients

00:46:19.950 --> 00:46:21.550
for a great educational
VR experience.

00:46:21.550 --> 00:46:22.820
And I've talked about
who's going to be

00:46:22.820 --> 00:46:23.954
involved in creating them.

00:46:23.954 --> 00:46:25.370
But it's still
really hard to give

00:46:25.370 --> 00:46:28.250
a roadmap of what the real
process is going to look like.

00:46:28.250 --> 00:46:30.740
With technology, ideas, and
patterns moving so quickly,

00:46:30.740 --> 00:46:33.530
it's really hard to guess what's
just six months down the road.

00:46:33.530 --> 00:46:35.030
So take it with a
grain of salt as I

00:46:35.030 --> 00:46:38.830
try to predict how the next
generation of educational VR

00:46:38.830 --> 00:46:40.820
experiences will come to be.

00:46:40.820 --> 00:46:45.030
I think it's going to start with
existing VR experiences that

00:46:45.030 --> 00:46:47.616
aren't necessarily
intended for education.

00:46:47.616 --> 00:46:49.490
VR game designers are
going to make something

00:46:49.490 --> 00:46:52.340
that's incredibly compelling
and that has a huge audience.

00:46:52.340 --> 00:46:55.140
From there, teachers are going
to recognize an opportunity

00:46:55.140 --> 00:46:57.850
to use that VR
framework for education.

00:46:57.850 --> 00:46:59.680
And "Minecraft"
gives a great example

00:46:59.680 --> 00:47:02.240
of a game that's already
been repurposed for education

00:47:02.240 --> 00:47:03.920
in all sorts of ways.

00:47:03.920 --> 00:47:05.670
From there, we're going
to have to involve

00:47:05.670 --> 00:47:07.900
the researchers to figure out
the appropriate metrics that

00:47:07.900 --> 00:47:10.316
allow us to measure the impact
of the app on the students'

00:47:10.316 --> 00:47:13.050
performance without compromising
the overall experience

00:47:13.050 --> 00:47:14.090
of that app.

00:47:14.090 --> 00:47:16.904
Working together, the designers,
teachers, and researchers

00:47:16.904 --> 00:47:18.820
are going to figure out
a way to put education

00:47:18.820 --> 00:47:22.340
at the core of that experience
rather than just making VR

00:47:22.340 --> 00:47:26.520
a light layer on top of what is
otherwise an educational app.

00:47:26.520 --> 00:47:29.160
What I really want you to take
away from these last few slides

00:47:29.160 --> 00:47:31.110
is that a great VR
educational experience will

00:47:31.110 --> 00:47:33.330
require multiple disciplines.

00:47:33.330 --> 00:47:35.540
We need to engage
new partners and get

00:47:35.540 --> 00:47:37.280
outside of our comfort zones.

00:47:37.280 --> 00:47:40.510
So I think they're going to play
off the stage pretty soon here.

00:47:40.510 --> 00:47:43.220
But I'm going to try
to have us all wrap up

00:47:43.220 --> 00:47:45.980
with our own conclusions.

00:47:45.980 --> 00:47:47.170
BEN SCHROM: Thanks, Rob.

00:47:47.170 --> 00:47:48.050
Yeah, so as I said
at the outset,

00:47:48.050 --> 00:47:49.300
we're really excited about VR.

00:47:49.300 --> 00:47:51.142
Hopefully, that's
pretty obvious by now.

00:47:51.142 --> 00:47:53.600
I think it's actually pretty
rare that we get opportunities

00:47:53.600 --> 00:47:57.080
like this as a community of
people that build technology.

00:47:57.080 --> 00:48:00.230
It's not rare to find
amazing technology like VR.

00:48:00.230 --> 00:48:02.860
And it's not rare to find
causes like education.

00:48:02.860 --> 00:48:06.910
But it's rare to find technology
like VR that can so profoundly

00:48:06.910 --> 00:48:10.320
scale solutions to an imperative
like education in a way

00:48:10.320 --> 00:48:12.610
that long-held
intuition in science

00:48:12.610 --> 00:48:15.290
has told us is the right way.

00:48:15.290 --> 00:48:17.640
If all of us, or even some
of us, get this right,

00:48:17.640 --> 00:48:19.680
it could change the way
that we teach and learn.

00:48:19.680 --> 00:48:21.060
And one of the
teachers, this one

00:48:21.060 --> 00:48:22.601
that we met on our
Expeditions panel,

00:48:22.601 --> 00:48:24.410
told us that the
superpower she most wants

00:48:24.410 --> 00:48:26.590
is to be able to make
eye contact with all 30

00:48:26.590 --> 00:48:28.700
of her students
at the same time.

00:48:28.700 --> 00:48:30.466
What an amazing idea.

00:48:30.466 --> 00:48:31.840
And it's probably
too late for us

00:48:31.840 --> 00:48:33.590
to have this amazing
teacher in our class.

00:48:33.590 --> 00:48:35.200
But it's probably
not too late for us

00:48:35.200 --> 00:48:37.440
to give her that superpower
in the near future.

00:48:37.440 --> 00:48:39.773
So we're just really, really
excited to see that happen.

00:48:42.749 --> 00:48:44.290
JENNIFER HOLLAND:
And virtual reality

00:48:44.290 --> 00:48:47.380
will never completely
replace physical field trips

00:48:47.380 --> 00:48:49.410
and travel, nor should they.

00:48:49.410 --> 00:48:53.500
But it's going to enable
experiences to happen when it

00:48:53.500 --> 00:48:56.230
would otherwise be impossible.

00:48:56.230 --> 00:48:59.970
And not only will it be a
democratizer of experience

00:48:59.970 --> 00:49:04.240
to individuals around the
world and schools and the home.

00:49:04.240 --> 00:49:07.050
It's going to be an
enabler of experiences

00:49:07.050 --> 00:49:10.980
to distant galaxies, and Mars,
and microscopic worlds that

00:49:10.980 --> 00:49:13.505
would otherwise be
virtually impossible.

00:49:16.420 --> 00:49:18.760
ROB JAGNOW: And I will
simply conclude by saying,

00:49:18.760 --> 00:49:21.890
I want you to be
prepared for surprises.

00:49:21.890 --> 00:49:23.680
That amazing VR
experience that is

00:49:23.680 --> 00:49:25.986
going to revolutionize
education probably

00:49:25.986 --> 00:49:27.360
isn't going to
look like anything

00:49:27.360 --> 00:49:29.100
you have ever seen before.

00:49:29.100 --> 00:49:31.380
And I hope somebody here
will help us find it.

00:49:31.380 --> 00:49:32.810
Thank you.

00:49:32.810 --> 00:49:34.570
[APPLAUSE]

